HOW TO MINE DUCO ON A TI-84 PLUS CE CALCULATOR

WHAT YOU NEED

TI-84 Plus CE calculator (not the older grey screen version)
Mini-USB to USB-A cable
Windows, Mac, or Linux computer
Internet connection

STEP 1: INSTALL THE TOOLCHAIN

On Windows

Go to CEmu website and download CE-Dev-Setup.exe
Run the installer
Check libusb and USBDRVCE when asked
Click Finish

On Mac

Open Terminal
git clone https://github.com/CE-Programming/toolchain
cd toolchain
./install.sh

On Linux

sudo apt-get install build-essential
git clone https://github.com/CE-Programming/toolchain
cd toolchain
./install.sh

STEP 2: INSTALL USB DRIVER

Open Terminal or Command Prompt

git clone https://github.com/commandblockguy/CE-serial
cd CE-serial
make

On Windows only you may need to install a driver called zadig

STEP 3: CREATE THE MINER CODE

Open any text editor (Notepad, VS Code, TextEdit)
Copy the DUCOMiner.c code from above
Save it as DUCOMiner.c
Save it inside the CE-serial folder

STEP 4: COMPILE THE CODE

Open Terminal or Command Prompt in the CE-serial folder

make DUCOMiner

If you see errors, check that you copied the code exactly.

STEP 5: SEND TO CALCULATOR

Plug your calculator into the computer with USB cable
On the calculator, press 2nd then Link (the button above Enter)
Press Receive
On your computer type

ticalc-usb send DUCOMiner.8xp

Wait for it to finish. The calculator will say Done.

STEP 6: SET UP THE PYTHON BRIDGE

Make sure Python 3 is installed from python.org
Install pyserial by typing

pip install pyserial

Copy the calc_bridge.py code from above
Save it as calc_bridge.py
Open the file and change this line

DUCO_USER = "YOUR_USERNAME_HERE"

to your actual Duino-Coin username

Find your calculator's serial port

On Windows look in Device Manager under Ports. It will say COM3, COM4, etc.

On Mac open Terminal and type ls /dev/tty.usb* It will show something like /dev/tty.usbmodem1234

On Linux open Terminal and type ls /dev/ttyUSB* It will show something like /dev/ttyUSB0

Change the COMPUTER_PORT line in calc_bridge.py to your port

STEP 7: RUN THE MINER

On the calculator, find DUCOMiner in the programs list and run it
You should see READY on the calculator screen
On your computer, open Terminal in the folder with calc_bridge.py
Type python calc_bridge.py
Press Enter

WHAT YOU SHOULD SEE

On the calculator you will see a screen showing hashes, accepted shares, and rejected shares. Dots will appear while mining. When a share is found it will say FOUND and the nonce number.

On your computer you will see Calculator ready, Connected to server, Job diff XX target XXXX, and ACCEPTED when you find shares.

TROUBLESHOOTING

Problem No calculator found

Check USB cable. Make sure calculator is in Receive mode. Try a different USB port.

Problem Calculator not responding

Press the reset button on the back of the calculator. Restart the program.

Problem Compilation errors

Make sure you copied the code exactly with no missing brackets. Check that the toolchain installed correctly.

Problem Bridge says Connection failed

Check your internet connection. Make sure DUCO_USER is changed to your username. Try port 2812 instead of 2811 in the code.

EXPECTED PERFORMANCE

TI-84 Plus CE will get about 500 to 1000 hashes per second which is roughly 1 to 2 DUCO per day.

Older TI-83 models will get about 50 to 100 hashes per second which is not worth it for profit but still fun for bragging rights.

